<article class="post-body wrap wrap-820" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/BlogPosting">
  <meta itemprop="headline" content="Physician-Administered IV Ketamine vs. At-Home Ketamine: What's the Clinical Difference?" />
  <meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2025-10-15" />
  <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Mary K. Moore, LPC" /></span>

  <!-- Key takeaways -->
  <div class="post-takeaways">
    <p class="post-takeaways-label">Key takeaways</p>
    <ul>
      <li>IV ketamine has higher and more predictable bioavailability than oral or at-home ketamine</li>
      <li>Physician presence means real-time medical monitoring, not remote support</li>
      <li>The evidence base for ketamine efficacy was built on supervised IV administration</li>
      <li>The integration therapy component is what produces lasting outcomes, not the drug alone</li>
      <li>LAP protocol: Zoom intake, Dr. Milling consult, supervised infusion, integration sessions</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>Ketamine therapy has become one of the most talked-about treatments for depression, PTSD, and other conditions that haven&rsquo;t responded to conventional approaches. With that attention has come a wave of options, from physician-supervised infusion clinics to app-based services that deliver ketamine lozenges to your front door.</p>

  <p>If you&rsquo;re researching ketamine therapy, you&rsquo;ll encounter this range. And the price differences are significant. So is the clinical difference.</p>

  <p>Here&rsquo;s what you need to understand before making a decision.</p>

  <h2>The Rise of At-Home Ketamine</h2>

  <p>Over the last several years, a number of companies have introduced at-home ketamine programs. These services typically involve a telehealth evaluation, a prescription for oral ketamine in lozenge or nasal spray form, and remote support during sessions via video call or app check-in.</p>

  <p>The appeal is clear: lower cost, greater accessibility, and no need to travel to a clinic. For some people, the familiar environment of home may also feel less intimidating than a medical setting.</p>

  <p>But the clinical picture is more complicated.</p>

  <h2>What At-Home Ketamine Is Missing</h2>

  <p>Oral ketamine has a different pharmacological profile than intravenous ketamine. When taken orally, ketamine has low and unpredictable bioavailability, typically 20 to 30% compared to nearly 100% for IV administration. This means dosing is less precise, onset is slower and harder to predict, and the therapeutic effect is more variable from session to session.</p>

  <p>More significantly: at-home programs are, by definition, unsupervised at the medical level.</p>

  <p>Ketamine can affect blood pressure, heart rate, and oxygen saturation. In a small percentage of people, it triggers dissociative episodes that are more intense than anticipated, or interacts with other medications in ways that require clinical management. With a physician present, these situations are caught and managed immediately. At home, they are not.</p>

  <p>This isn&rsquo;t a theoretical concern. It&rsquo;s the reason ketamine infusions have historically been administered in clinical settings by medical professionals.</p>

  <h2>The LAP Model: Physician-Present IV Ketamine</h2>

  <p>At Lake Austin Psychotherapy, ketamine is administered intravenously by Dr. Truman Milling, a board-certified emergency physician with 60+ peer-reviewed publications in some of the most rigorous medical journals in the world, including the New England Journal of Medicine.</p>

  <p>Dr. Milling is present for the entire infusion. He monitors vital signs, manages the patient&rsquo;s medical response in real time, and adjusts dosing as needed. After the infusion, Mary Moore, the therapist, provides immediate integration support while the window of neuroplasticity is still open.</p>

  <p>This is a fundamentally different clinical model than a video call with a support coordinator.</p>

  <h2>Why Physician Presence Matters for Outcome</h2>

  <p>The evidence base for ketamine therapy has been built almost entirely on IV administration in supervised clinical settings. The 2021 study in the American Journal of Psychiatry that showed 67 to 71% response rates for treatment-resistant depression used IV ketamine with medical supervision, not oral lozenges delivered to someone&rsquo;s living room.</p>

  <p>When at-home services cite research showing ketamine&rsquo;s efficacy, they are citing studies that were done in settings much closer to what we offer than to what they offer.</p>

  <p>There&rsquo;s also the integration component. The period immediately following a ketamine infusion is one of the most therapeutically significant windows available in mental health treatment. The brain&rsquo;s NMDA receptors have been disrupted, neuroplasticity is elevated, and the person is more available for therapeutic work than usual. This is not the moment to be alone with a phone number to call if something feels wrong. This is the moment for skilled therapeutic support.</p>

  <p>Our model pairs each infusion with immediate integration work led by an experienced therapist. This is why our clients report sustained relief for months following a single infusion, not just the day of.</p>

  <h2>The Therapy Component Isn&rsquo;t Optional</h2>

  <p>This brings up something important that gets missed in a lot of ketamine marketing: the drug is not the treatment. The drug creates a neurobiological opportunity. The treatment is what you do with that opportunity.</p>

  <p>Ketamine Assisted Psychotherapy, as opposed to ketamine infusion alone, means the therapeutic work is built around the pharmacological window. There&rsquo;s preparation before the infusion, support during it, and structured integration afterward. Without the therapy component, clients often experience relief in the short term that fades within weeks.</p>

  <p>At-home programs vary widely in the quality and depth of their therapeutic support. Some offer meaningful integration sessions; many offer a brief check-in call and a journaling prompt. The difference in outcomes reflects this.</p>

  <h2>What Our Intake Process Looks Like</h2>

  <p>We don&rsquo;t take everyone. Before any infusion, Dr. Milling conducts a thorough medical evaluation that screens for contraindications including active psychosis, recent cardiovascular events, bladder inflammation, and certain medication interactions. This isn&rsquo;t a checkbox exercise. It&rsquo;s a genuine clinical consultation.</p>

  <p>From there:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Zoom intake</strong> with Mary Moore: history, goals, preparation</li>
    <li><strong>Medical consult</strong> with Dr. Milling: screening, questions, informed consent</li>
    <li><strong>Infusion session</strong> at our Westlake Hills office: <strong>physician-monitored IV infusion</strong> with therapeutic support</li>
    <li><strong>Integration sessions</strong> by telehealth in the days following</li>
  </ol>

  <p>Private luxury transport is available from Austin, Houston, Dallas, and San Antonio for clients who need it.</p>

  <h2>Who Ketamine Assisted Psychotherapy Is For</h2>

  <p>KAP is best suited for people who:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Have tried two or more antidepressants without adequate response (treatment-resistant depression)</li>
    <li>Have PTSD that hasn&rsquo;t responded sufficiently to trauma-focused therapy</li>
    <li>Are managing conditions including bipolar depression, OCD, or eating disorders that have proven difficult to treat</li>
    <li>Are seeking an alternative or adjunct to ongoing medication management</li>
    <li>Are committed to the integration work, not just the pharmacological experience</li>
  </ul>

  <p>It is not a good fit for people looking for a recreational-adjacent experience, those who aren&rsquo;t prepared to engage in therapeutic work, or those with contraindicated medical histories.</p>

  <h2>A Note on Cost</h2>

  <p>Physician-administered IV ketamine with integrated psychotherapy costs more than at-home services. We&rsquo;re transparent about that.</p>

  <p>What clients often tell us is that after years of medication trials, multiple therapists, and time lost to a condition that didn&rsquo;t respond to conventional treatment, the cost of one well-designed infusion series is a different kind of calculation than it first appears to be.</p>

  <p>We offer a free one-hour consultation to determine whether KAP is likely to be effective for your specific situation before you make any commitment.</p>

